## The unit of analysis — the beat

### Grounding

The beat is the atomic unit of this study. Its definition is grounded in Jerome Bruner's narrative theory (1986, 1991) and Kenneth Burke's dramatistic pentad (1945).

Bruner's central argument is that narrative is built around **canonicity and breach**: a canonical state (what is expected, the established order) and a breach of that state (something that violates the expectation). The breach is what makes something worth narrating. Without a breach, there is no story, only background.

Burke identifies the structural elements that make a narrative unit: an Agent, an Action, a Goal, a Setting, an Instrument — and Trouble. Trouble is generated by a mismatch between any two of those elements. When they are in balance, nothing happens. When they are out of balance, a story begins.

Bruner also identifies a **dual landscape** in every narrative: a landscape of action (what happens) and a landscape of consciousness (what the protagonist thinks, feels, intends, doubts). Both are necessary. Action without consciousness is myth. Consciousness without action is nothing.

### Application to this project

Every voice note in this corpus operates on Bruner's dual landscape. The landscape of action is the AI interaction — what was built, attempted, failed, or discovered. The landscape of consciousness is the emotional register — what was felt, expected, or surprised.

A beat is not defined by what fields it contains. It is defined by what generates it.

**Operational definition:**

*A beat is a unit of experience bounded by a breach of expectation in an AI interaction. It opens when the narrator's prior model of the tool — what it can do, what she can do with it, or how she relates to it — is violated, either positively or negatively. It closes when the narrator reaches a response to that breach (reframe, integration, resolution) or explicitly names the tension as unresolved. An entry with no breach produces no beats.*

### Implications

Multiple beats in a single entry means multiple distinct breaches — not multiple emotions. If Entry 07 produces three beats it is because three separate expectations were violated: the deployment failed (breach 1), the UX gap between using Claude and building with it became visible (breach 2), the failure was reframed through design principles (breach 3).

An entry with no AI-triggered breach produces an empty array. Not a beat with a neutral emotion — an empty array.

